description:
secretx-systemd/src/lib.rs:85-89:

    if name.contains('/') {
        return Err(SecretError::InvalidUri(
            "systemd credential name must not contain \`/\` (path traversal not allowed)".into(),
        ));
    }

The parenthetical 'path traversal not allowed' implies a comprehensive defence. The actual check is one byte. Names like '..', '.', and percent-encoded NUL are accepted (see crate-secretsx-0hfd.1 for the full list).

A user who reads this error and concludes 'good, my system rejects path-traversal patterns' is mistaken. A future contributor who reads this and concludes 'no need to add stricter checks, we already protect against traversal' is mistaken.

Either:
  (a) tighten the validation to actually prevent traversal patterns (the fix in 0hfd.1), and rephrase the message accordingly, or
  (b) shorten the message to factual scope: 'systemd credential name must not contain \`/\`' — drop the parenthetical.
